{"title_page": "Soliloquy for Lilith", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Soliloquy for Lilith\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Nurse with Wound]]\n| cover      = solforlil.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1988\n| recorded   = May 1988\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Industrial music|Industrial]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[drone music|drone]]|[[Aleatoric music|chance music]]}}\n| length     = 106:43\n| label      = Idle Hole\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Steven Stapleton]]|Diana Rogerson}}\n| prev_title = [[Spiral Insana]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[A Sucked Orange]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|4|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r214709|pure_url=yes}}] |}}\n\n'''''Soliloquy for Lilith''''' is an album by English [[experimental music|experimental]] project [[Nurse with Wound]], originally released in 1988 by the label Idle Hole that had been created for the album's release by project leader [[Steven Stapleton]], and later reissued several times by varying record labels. It is considered one of the project's greatest albums, as well as a long-standing [[Industrial music|industrial]] [[drone music|drone]] record best known for its [[Aleatoric music|chance]] method of composition.\n\n==Background and recording==\nThe album was recorded by Steven Stapleton and his wife Diana Rogerson, credited as Calhoun Phelan in the album's liner notes, in May 1988. No instruments per se were used on the record; the only sound source was a number of [[effects unit]]s which he had set up to operate in a [[feedback loop]]. There was no original input signal being processed, simply the feedback hum generated by plugging the original chain of pedals back into itself. However, when Stapleton went near the pedals he found the sound changed in accordance with his proximity to the various pedals and units. \n\nStapleton told author [[David Keenan]] (in the book ''England's Hidden Reverse'') that he had then essentially created the album's compositions by gently moving his fingers above the various units to create the slow, subtle changes in sound, tone and timbre; in later years he has put the album down to an electrical fault of some sort in the studio it was recorded in. This was acknowledged on a later reissue with the credit \"''our thanks to Electricity for making this recording possible''\". He remains proud of the album, describing it to Keenan as \"fucking brilliant\". The album title refers to Stapleton and Rogerson's daughter Lilith who was born that year; Lilith would go on to contribute both artwork and vocals to releases by NWW and [[Current 93]].\n\n==Release history==\nDespite being a limited edition three-record set in an embossed box, which made it a more expensive album to package, the album was one of the most successful NWW releases of Stapleton's career, and reissues since its original release have continued to sell; Stapleton also told Keenan that the sales of the album funded his and his family's move to Cooloorta in [[County Clare]], [[Ireland]] in 1989. Originally issued on the short-lived Idle Hole label (founded by Stapleton and Rogerson with a government [[Enterprise Allowance Scheme]] grant), a small overrun of the third disc was issued separately as ''Soliloquy For Lilith Parts 5 & 6''. The album was reissued as a double CD on United Dairies via [[World Serpent Distribution|World Serpent]] in 1993 and then again in 2003, this time as a 3 disc set mirroring the box packaging of the original with the third disc containing two remixes of the original material by Stapleton and Colin Potter. When World Serpent Distribution went out of business in 2004, the 3-CD set was reissued by United Jnana (a hook-up between Stapleton's label United Dairies and Mark Logan's label Jnana Records), this present edition being identical in all but catalogue number from its predecessor.\n\nThe album's original six selections follow a strict convention: each is between 17 and 18 minutes in length. Later editions featured two bonus selections. Of these, the first (VII) was a remix of the original album's third selection, with additional effects and using the latter as a backing track, each running for the same length. The later bonus track runs for over 20 minutes.\n\nReleases of the album commonly feature depictions of the [[Burney Relief]] in the album artwork;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Nurse-With-Wound-Soliloquy-For-Lilith/release/429811|title=Soliloquy for Lilith (1)|work=Discogs.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Nurse-With-Wound-Soliloquy-For-Lilith/release/7223050|title=Soliloquy for Lilith (2)|work=Discogs.com}}</ref> the significance of this is that the central figure depicted has been identified with [[Lilith]].<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.ancient.eu/article/658/the-queen-of-the-night/ |title=The Queen of the Night |author=Joshua J. Mark |date=February 19, 2014 |website=ancient.eu}}</ref>\n\n[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]] ranked it the 54th best album of the 80s with [[Aaron Turner]] of [[Isis (band)|Isis]] calling it \"one of the most listenable and enduring albums from the vast NWW catalog\".<ref>[http://www.factmag.com/2013/06/24/the-100-best-albums-of-the-1980s-100-81/48/]</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Steven Stapleton]] and Diana Rogerson\n| title1 = [untitled]\n| length1 = 17:56\n| extra1 = \n| title2 = [untitled]\n| length2 = 17:06\n| extra2 = \n| title3 = [untitled]\n| length3 = 17:51\n| extra3 =\n| title4 = [untitled]\n| length4 = 17:51\n| extra4 =\n| title5 = [untitled]\n| length5 = 17:29\n| extra5 =\n| title6 = [untitled]\n| length6 = 17:30\n| extra6 = \n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Bonus tracks (2003/2005 editions)\n| collapsed = yes\n| title7 = [untitled]\n| length7 = 18:54\n| extra7 = \n| title8 = [untitled]\n| length8 = 20:52\n| extra8 = \n}}\n\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://brainwashed.com/common/htdocs/discog/ud035.php?site=nww Page at official NWW website for Soliloquy For Lilith]\n*England's Hidden Reverse - David Keenan, SAF 2003 {{ISBN|0-946719-40-3}}\n\n{{Nurse with Wound}}\n\n[[Category:Nurse with Wound albums]]\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Soliloquy for Lilith\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Nurse with Wound]]\n| cover      = solforlil.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1988\n| recorded   = May 1988\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Industrial music|Industrial]]|[[experimental music|experimental]]|[[drone music|drone]]|[[Aleatoric music|chance music]]}}\n| length     = 106:43\n| label      = Idle Hole\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Steven Stapleton]]|Diana Rogerson}}\n| prev_title = [[Spiral Insana]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[A Sucked Orange]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|4|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r214709|pure_url=yes}}] |}}\n\n'''''Soliloquy for Lilith''''' is an album by English [[experimental music|experimental]] project [[Nurse with Wound]], originally released in 1988 by the label Idle Hole that had been created for the album's release by project leader [[Steven Stapleton]], and later reissued several times by varying record labels. It is considered one of the project's greatest albums. as well as a long-standing [[Industrial music|industrial]] [[drone music|drone]] record best known for its [[Aleatoric music|chance]] method of composition.\n\n==Background and recording==\nThe album was recorded by Steven Stapleton and his wife Diana Rogerson, credited as Calhoun Phelan in the album's liner notes, in May 1988. No instruments per se were used on the record; the only sound source was a number of [[effects unit]]s which he had set up to operate in a [[feedback loop]]. There was no original input signal being processed, simply the feedback hum generated by plugging the original chain of pedals back into itself. However, when Stapleton went near the pedals he found the sound changed in accordance with his proximity to the various pedals and units. \n\nStapleton told author [[David Keenan]] (in the book ''England's Hidden Reverse'') that he had then essentially created the album's compositions by gently moving his fingers above the various units to create the slow, subtle changes in sound, tone and timbre; in later years he has put the album down to an electrical fault of some sort in the studio it was recorded in. This was acknowledged on a later reissue with the credit \"''our thanks to Electricity for making this recording possible''\". He remains proud of the album, describing it to Keenan as \"fucking brilliant\". The album title refers to Stapleton and Rogerson's daughter Lilith who was born that year; Lilith would go on to contribute both artwork and vocals to releases by NWW and [[Current 93]].\n\n==Release history==\nDespite being a limited edition three-record set in an embossed box, which made it a more expensive album to package, the album was one of the most successful NWW releases of Stapleton's career, and reissues since its original release have continued to sell; Stapleton also told Keenan that the sales of the album funded his and his family's move to Cooloorta in [[County Clare]], [[Ireland]] in 1989. Originally issued on the short-lived Idle Hole label (founded by Stapleton and Rogerson with a government [[Enterprise Allowance Scheme]] grant), a small overrun of the third disc was issued separately as ''Soliloquy For Lilith Parts 5 & 6''. The album was reissued as a double CD on United Dairies via [[World Serpent Distribution|World Serpent]] in 1993 and then again in 2003, this time as a 3 disc set mirroring the box packaging of the original with the third disc containing two remixes of the original material by Stapleton and Colin Potter. When World Serpent Distribution went out of business in 2004, the 3-CD set was reissued by United Jnana (a hook-up between Stapleton's label United Dairies and Mark Logan's label Jnana Records), this present edition being identical in all but catalogue number from its predecessor.\n\nThe album's original six selections follow a strict convention: each is between 17 and 18 minutes in length. Later editions featured two bonus selections. Of these, the first (VII) was a remix of the original album's third selection, with additional effects and using the latter as a backing track, each running for the same length. The later bonus track runs for over 20 minutes.\n\nReleases of the album commonly feature depictions of the [[Burney Relief]] in the album artwork;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Nurse-With-Wound-Soliloquy-For-Lilith/release/429811|title=Soliloquy for Lilith (1)|work=Discogs.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Nurse-With-Wound-Soliloquy-For-Lilith/release/7223050|title=Soliloquy for Lilith (2)|work=Discogs.com}}</ref> the significance of this is that the central figure depicted has been identified with [[Lilith]].<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.ancient.eu/article/658/the-queen-of-the-night/ |title=The Queen of the Night |author=Joshua J. Mark |date=February 19, 2014 |website=ancient.eu}}</ref>\n\n[[Fact (UK magazine)|FACT]] ranked it the 54th best album of the 80s with [[Aaron Turner]] of [[Isis (band)|Isis]] calling it \"one of the most listenable and enduring albums from the vast NWW catalog\".<ref>[http://www.factmag.com/2013/06/24/the-100-best-albums-of-the-1980s-100-81/48/]</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Steven Stapleton]] and Diana Rogerson\n| title1 = [untitled]\n| length1 = 17:56\n| extra1 = \n| title2 = [untitled]\n| length2 = 17:06\n| extra2 = \n| title3 = [untitled]\n| length3 = 17:51\n| extra3 =\n| title4 = [untitled]\n| length4 = 17:51\n| extra4 =\n| title5 = [untitled]\n| length5 = 17:29\n| extra5 =\n| title6 = [untitled]\n| length6 = 17:30\n| 