{"title_page": "Gershon Hundert", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian historian of Polish Jewish history (b. 1946)}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Gershon David Hundert\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = 1946\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Canada]]\n| residence          = [[Montreal]], [[Canada]]\n| occupation         = Historian, Professor\n| title              = Leanor Segal Professor\n| alma_mater         = [[Columbia University]]\n| discipline         = [[Jewish History]]\n| sub_discipline     = Polish Jewish History\n| workplaces         = [[McGill University]]\n}}\n\n'''Gershon David Hundert''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|FRSC}} (b. 1946) is a noted [[Canadian]] historian of [[History of the Jews in Poland|Early Modern Polish Jewry]] and Leanor Segal Professor at [[McGill University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/history/gershon-hundert|title=Gershon Hundert|website=History and Classical Studies}}</ref><ref name=\"mcgill.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/jewishstudies/faculty/hundert|title=Gershon D. Hundert|website=Jewish Studies \u05de\u05d3\u05e2\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn to a Jewish family in Toronto, Gershon Hundert is one of the three sons of Charles and Norma Hundert and a third generation immigrant from Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Charles-Hundert/6000000015677912581|title=Charles Saul Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref> His paternal grandparents arrived in Canada in the early 1910s from [[Obertyn]] (part of the [[Ruthenian Voivodeship]] in the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] before [[Second Partition of Poland|the Second Partition in 1792]], western Ukraine today) and maternal grandparents from [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Szmelke-Hundert/6000000020378665030|title=Szmelke Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Louis-Hundert/6000000015678331406|title=Louis Leibish Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref>\n\nHundert received his B.A. from [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]] and [[Columbia University School of General Studies|School of General Studies at Columbia University]] (1968) and M.A. from [[Ohio State University]] (1971), where he wrote a thesis on 18th-Century Hasidic Rabbi [[Abraham Kalisker]] under the supervision of [[Zvi Ankori]] (1920-2012), a specialist of Byzantine Karaites and a student of [[Salo Baron]].<ref>Gershon David Hundert,\u00a0\u201cToward a Biography of R. Abraham Kalisker,\u201d (Master Thesis, Ohio State University, 1971).</ref>\n\nFollowing Ankori, Hundert returned to Columbia to pursue a doctorate degree in history. He primarily studied with {{ill|Andrzej Kaminski|pl|Andrzej Sulima Kami\u0144ski}} (b. 1935), political and diplomatic historian of early modern Poland-Lithuania, and completed his dissertation in 1978 titled \u201cSecurity and Dependence: Perspectives on Seventeenth-century Polish-Jewish Society Gained Through a Study of Jewish Merchants in Little Poland.\u201d<ref>Gershon David Hundert, \u201cSecurity and Dependence: Perspectives on Seventeenth-century Polish-Jewish Society Gained Through a Study of Jewish Merchants in Little Poland,\u201d (PhD. Diss., Columbia University, 1978).</ref> He was also deeply influenced and mentored by Israel historian {{ill|Jacob Goldberg|de}} (1924-2011), the pioneer scholar of Polish-Jewish relations.<ref>For Hundert\u2019s three teachers, see Gershon David Hundert, \u201cSecurity and Dependence,\u201d xxvi-xxvii, and Gershon David Hundert, ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1992), 227-228.</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Hundert came back to Canada and taught at [[McGill University]] ever since. He was appointed as lecturer (1975-1978), assistant professor (1978-1983), associate professor (1983-1992), Montreal Jewish Community Professor of Jewish Studies (1993-2002), and currently Leanor Segal Professor of Jewish Studies (since 2002). He has served as Department Chair of Jewish Studies twice (1984-1988 and 1998-2007). He also held visiting professorships at [[Harvard]], [[Yale]] and [[the Hebrew University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/students/courses/files/students.courses/UGART212.pdf |title=Part two, Faculty of Arts section, 2001-2002 Undergraduate Programs Calendar, McGill University |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/students/courses/files/students.courses/UGART02B.pdf |title=Faculty of Arts, Part 3, 2002-2003 Undergraduate Programs Calendar, McGill University |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref> He was the editor-in-chief of ''[[The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe]]'' (2008) and an elected fellow of [[the Royal Society of Canada]] (2011- ).<ref>The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe, edited by Gershon David Hundert (Yale univ. press, 2008)</ref>\n\nHundert is married to Ruth, daughter of notable WWII Veteran [[Nathaniel Mencow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegram.com/article/20070528/OBIT/705280310|title=Nathaniel Mencow, 89|publisher=}}</ref> They raised one son and two daughters.\n\n==Scholarly Contributions==\nSucceeding {{ill|Raphael Mahler|pl}} and {{ill|Ignacy Schipper|de}}, Gershon Hundert represents the postwar-born generation of premodern Polish Jewish historians and, along with [[Moshe Rosman]] and {{ill|Ada Rapoport-Albert|he|\u05e2\u05d3\u05d4_\u05e8\u05e4\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d8-\u05d0\u05dc\u05d1\u05e8\u05d8}}, establishes \u201ca new era of the historiography of Polish Jewry.\u201d <ref>Gershon Bacon, Review of ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century'', by Gershon David Hundert, The Jewish Quarterly Review 86, No. 3/4 (Jan. - Apr., 1996): 419.</ref>\n\nHis first monograph, ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town'' (1992), studies social and economic history of [[Opat\u00f3w]] Jewry in the eighteenth century, exemplifying Jewish autonomy and identity and their crucial commercial roles in the later period of the Commonwealth. The work also sheds new light on Polish local history and Jewish microhistory.\n\nHis more renowned second monograph, ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century'' (2004), is an essential revisionist work in early modern European Jewish historiography. It examines the life of the understudied, but extremely important, East Central European Jewry\u2014world's largest Jewish community at the time, and argues for their ''mentalit\u00e9'' of chosenness and their particularities on the path towards modernity.\n\nAnother achievement is the groundbreaking ''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'' published in 2008. 450 leading scholars from the world have contributed to this decade-long project, of which Hundert served as the editor-in-chief. The work includes more than 1,800 entries and covers all aspects of Eastern European Jewish experiences from the Middle Ages to the late twentieth century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/about.aspx|title=YIVO - Preface to the Print Edition|website=www.yivoencyclopedia.org}}</ref> The searchable version of the encyclopedia was launched in 2010.\n\nBesides, he edited an essay collection on the development of scholarship on Hasidism in 1991 and co-compiled a bibliography on Eastern European Jewish historiography in 1984.\n\n==Awards and Honours==\n* President, American Academy for Jewish Research, 2014-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/ajs-perspectives/ajs-magazine-spring-2018-2.pdf |title=Perspectives magazine |date=2018 |website=www.associationforjewishstudies.org |format=PDF}}</ref>\n* Fellow, the Royal Society of Canada, Academy of the Arts and Humanities, 2011-\n* The Judaica Reference Award, from Association of Jewish Libraries, for Gershon Hundert, editor-in-chief,\u00a0''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'',  2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300119039/yivo-encyclopedia-jews-eastern-europe|title=YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe - Yale University Press|website=yalebooks.yale.edu}}</ref>\n* Fellow, the Institute for Advanced Studies, Hebrew University, Jerusalem, 2007-2008.\n* Fellow, the American Academy for Jewish Research, 2006- .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aajr.org/officers-fellows/|title=Officers and Fellows|website=www.aajr.org|access-date=2018-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520114741/http://www.aajr.org/officers-fellows/|archive-date=2018-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* I. J. Segal Prize, for the best non-fiction book on a Jewish theme by a Canadian, for\u00a0''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity'', 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishbookreview.wordpress.com/2010/12/06/j-i-segel-awards-announced/|title=J.I. Segel Awards Announced|date=6 December 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Oscar Halecki Polish and East Central European History Award, for ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity'', 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.piasa.org/awards.html|title=Annual Awards Ceremony|website=www.piasa.org}}</ref>\n* Doctor of Humane Letters (honoris causa), Reconstructionist Rabbinical College, Philadelphia, PA, 2003.\n* Montreal Jewish Community Professor of Jewish Studies 1994-2002.\n* Leanor Segal Professor of Jewish Studies, McGill University, 2002- .<ref name=\"mcgill.ca\"/>\n\n==Selected Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity.'' University of California Press, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|978-0520238442}}\n/ {{ISBN|978-0520249943}}. (Also published in Russian, Hebrew, Polish and Lithuanian).\n\n* ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century.'' The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0801842733}}.\n* ''The Jews in Poland and Russia: Bibliographical Essays'' (with [[Gershon Bacon]]). Indiana University Press, 1984. {{ISBN|978-0253331588}}.\n\n===Edited Books / Encyclopedia===\n* ''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'', 2 vols., Editor in Chief. New Haven and London: Yale University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0300119039}}.\nhttp://www.yivoencyclopedia.org - launched 2010.\n\n* ''Jews in Early Modern Poland''. [Polin, Volume 10] Oxford: The Littman Library of Jewish Civilization in association with Vallentine Mitchell, 1997. {{ISBN|978-1874774310}}.\n* ''Jews, Poles, Socialists: The Failure of an Ideal''. [Polin, Volume 9] (edited with [[Antony Polonsky]], [[Israel Bartal]], [[Magdalena Opalski]] and [[Jerzy Tomaszewski (historian)|Jerzy Tomaszewski]]). Oxford: The Littman Library of Jewish Civilization in association with Vallentine Mitchell, 1996. {{ISBN|9781874774211}}.\n* ''Essential Papers on Hasidism: Origins to Present''. New York University Press, 1991. {{ISBN|978-0814734704}}.\n* ''Community and the Individual Jew: Essays in Honor of Lavy M. Becker''. (edited with Ronald S. Aigen). Montreal, Reconstructionist Rabbinical College Press, 1986. {{ISBN|978-0938945000}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\nTalk: Record of Jewish Merchant from the 18th Century, the Newest Materials.\n* https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t36ln-WbOyY\n\nTalk: Jews and Other Poles: Problems of Language.\n* https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oyEUk6po164\n\nInterview after the FRSC Election: https://blogs.mcgill.ca/jewishstudies/2011/11/22/interview-with-professor-gershon-hundert/\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hundert, Gershon}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian historians]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Polish historians]]\n[[Category:McGill University faculty]]\n[[Category:Columbia University School of General Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Canada]]\n[[Category:Jewish Theological Seminary of America alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian historians]]\n[[Category:Canadian historians of religion]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian historian of Polish Jewish history (b. 1946)}}\n{{more footnotes|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Gershon David Hundert\n| image              = \n| birth_date         = 1946\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Canada]]\n| residence          = [[Montreal]], [[Canada]]\n| occupation         = Historian, Professor\n| title              = Leanor Segal Professor\n| alma_mater         = [[Columbia University]]\n| discipline         = [[Jewish History]]\n| sub_discipline     = Polish Jewish History\n| workplaces         = [[McGill University]]\n}}\n\n'''Gershon David Hundert''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|FRSC}} (b. 1946) is a noted [[Canadian]] historian of [[History of the Jews in Poland|Early Modern Polish Jewry]] and Leanor Segal Professor at [[McGill University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/history/gershon-hundert|title=Gershon Hundert|website=History and Classical Studies}}</ref><ref name=\"mcgill.ca\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/jewishstudies/faculty/hundert|title=Gershon D. Hundert|website=Jewish Studies \u05de\u05d3\u05e2\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d9\u05d4\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn to a Jewish family in Toronto, Gershon Hundert is one of the three sons of Charles and Norma Hundert and a third generation immigrant from Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Charles-Hundert/6000000015677912581|title=Charles Saul Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref> His paternal grandparents arrived in Canada in the early 1910s from [[Obertyn]] (part of the [[Ruthenian Voivodeship]] in the [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]] before [[Second Partition of Poland|the Second Partition in 1792]], western Ukraine today) and maternal grandparents from [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Szmelke-Hundert/6000000020378665030|title=Szmelke Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Louis-Hundert/6000000015678331406|title=Louis Leibish Hundert|website=geni_family_tree}}</ref> \n\nHundert received his B.A. from [[Jewish Theological Seminary of America|Jewish Theological Seminary]] and [[Columbia University School of General Studies|School of General Studies at Columbia University]] (1968) and M.A. from [[Ohio State University]] (1971), where he wrote a thesis on 18th-Century Hasidic Rabbi [[Abraham Kalisker]] under the supervision of [[Zvi Ankori]] (1920-2012), a specialist of Byzantine Karaites and a student of [[Salo Baron]].<ref>Gershon David Hundert,\u00a0\u201cToward a Biography of R. Abraham Kalisker,\u201d (Master Thesis, Ohio State University, 1971).</ref>\n\nFollowing Ankori, Hundert returned to Columbia to pursue a doctorate degree in history. He primarily studied with {{ill|Andrzej Kaminski|pl|Andrzej Sulima Kami\u0144ski}} (b. 1935), political and diplomatic historian of early modern Poland-Lithuania, and completed his dissertation in 1978 titled \u201cSecurity and Dependence: Perspectives on Seventeenth-century Polish-Jewish Society Gained Through a Study of Jewish Merchants in Little Poland.\u201d<ref>Gershon David Hundert, \u201cSecurity and Dependence: Perspectives on Seventeenth-century Polish-Jewish Society Gained Through a Study of Jewish Merchants in Little Poland,\u201d (PhD. Diss., Columbia University, 1978).</ref> He was also deeply influenced and mentored by Israel historian {{ill|Jacob Goldberg|de}} (1924-2011), the pioneer scholar of Polish-Jewish relations.<ref>For Hundert\u2019s three teachers, see Gershon David Hundert, \u201cSecurity and Dependence,\u201d xxvi-xxvii, and Gershon David Hundert, ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century'' (Baltimore: The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1992), 227-228.</ref> \n\nIn 1975, Hundert came back to Canada and taught at [[McGill University]] ever since. He was appointed as lecturer (1975-1978), assistant professor (1978-1983), associate professor (1983-1992), Montreal Jewish Community Professor of Jewish Studies (1993-2002), and currently Leanor Segal Professor of Jewish Studies (since 2002). He has served as Department Chair of Jewish Studies twice (1984-1988 and 1998-2007). He also held visiting professorships at [[Harvard]], [[Yale]] and [[the Hebrew University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/students/courses/files/students.courses/UGART212.pdf |title=Part two, Faculty of Arts section, 2001-2002 Undergraduate Programs Calendar, McGill University |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/students/courses/files/students.courses/UGART02B.pdf |title=Faculty of Arts, Part 3, 2002-2003 Undergraduate Programs Calendar, McGill University |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2018-11-30}}</ref> He was the editor-in-chief of ''[[The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe]]'' (2008) and an elected fellow of [[the Royal Society of Canada]] (2011- ).<ref>The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe, edited by Gershon David Hundert (Yale univ. press, 2008)</ref>\n\nHundert is married to Ruth, daughter of notable WWII Veteran [[Nathaniel Mencow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegram.com/article/20070528/OBIT/705280310|title=Nathaniel Mencow, 89|publisher=}}</ref> They raised one son and two daughters.\n\n==Scholarly Contributions==\nSucceeding {{ill|Raphael Mahler|pl}} and {{ill|Ignacy Schipper|de}}, Gershon Hundert represents the postwar-born generation of premodern Polish Jewish historians and, along with [[Moshe Rosman]] and {{ill|Ada Rapoport-Albert|he|\u05e2\u05d3\u05d4_\u05e8\u05e4\u05e4\u05d5\u05e8\u05d8-\u05d0\u05dc\u05d1\u05e8\u05d8}}, establishes \u201ca new era of the historiography of Polish Jewry.\u201d <ref>Gershon Bacon, Review of ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century'', by Gershon David Hundert, The Jewish Quarterly Review 86, No. 3/4 (Jan. - Apr., 1996): 419.</ref>\n\nHis first monograph, ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town'' (1992), studies social and economic history of [[Opat\u00f3w]] Jewry in the eighteenth century, exemplifying Jewish autonomy and identity and their crucial commercial roles in the later period of the Commonwealth. The work also sheds new light on Polish local history and Jewish microhistory. \n\nHis more renowned second monograph, ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century'' (2004), is an essential revisionist work in early modern European Jewish historiography. It examines the life of the understudied, but extremely important, East Central European Jewry -- world's largest Jewish community at the time, and argues for their ''mentalit\u00e9'' of chosenness and their particularities on the path towards modernity. \n\nAnother achievement is the groundbreaking ''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'' published in 2008. 450 leading scholars from the world have contributed to this decade-long project, of which Hundert served as the editor-in-chief. The work includes more than 1,800 entries and covers all aspects of Eastern European Jewish experiences from the Middle Ages to the late twentieth century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/about.aspx|title=YIVO - Preface to the Print Edition|website=www.yivoencyclopedia.org}}</ref> The searchable version of the encyclopedia was launched in 2010. \n\nBesides, he edited an essay collection on the development of scholarship on Hasidism in 1991 and co-compiled a bibliography on Eastern European Jewish historiography in 1984.\n\n==Awards and Honours==\n* President, American Academy for Jewish Research, 2014-2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.associationforjewishstudies.org/docs/default-source/ajs-perspectives/ajs-magazine-spring-2018-2.pdf |title=Perspectives magazine |date=2018 |website=www.associationforjewishstudies.org |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n* Fellow, the Royal Society of Canada, Academy of the Arts and Humanities, 2011-\n\n* The Judaica Reference Award, from Association of Jewish Libraries, for Gershon Hundert, editor-in-chief,\u00a0''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'',  2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yalebooks.yale.edu/book/9780300119039/yivo-encyclopedia-jews-eastern-europe|title=YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe - Yale University Press|website=yalebooks.yale.edu}}</ref>\n\n* Fellow, the Institute for Advanced Studies, Hebrew University, Jerusalem, 2007-2008.\n\n* Fellow, the American Academy for Jewish Research, 2006- .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aajr.org/officers-fellows/|title=Officers and Fellows|website=www.aajr.org|access-date=2018-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520114741/http://www.aajr.org/officers-fellows/|archive-date=2018-05-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n* I. J. Segal Prize, for the best non-fiction book on a Jewish theme by a Canadian, for\u00a0''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity'', 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishbookreview.wordpress.com/2010/12/06/j-i-segel-awards-announced/|title=J.I. Segel Awards Announced|date=6 December 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n* Oscar Halecki Polish and East Central European History Award, for ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity'', 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.piasa.org/awards.html|title=Annual Awards Ceremony|website=www.piasa.org}}</ref>\n\n* Doctor of Humane Letters (honoris causa), Reconstructionist Rabbinical College, Philadelphia, PA, 2003.\n\n* Montreal Jewish Community Professor of Jewish Studies 1994-2002.\n\n* Leanor Segal Professor of Jewish Studies, McGill University, 2002- .<ref name=\"mcgill.ca\"/>\n\n==Selected Publications==\n\n===Books===\n* ''Jews in Poland-Lithuania in the Eighteenth Century: A Genealogy of Modernity.'' University of California Press, 2004 (Paperback, 2006). {{ISBN|978-0520238442}}\n/ {{ISBN|978-0520249943}}. (Also published in Russian, Hebrew, Polish and Lithuanian).\n\n* ''The Jews in a Polish Private Town: The Case of Opat\u00f3w in the Eighteenth Century.'' The Johns Hopkins University Press, 1992. {{ISBN|978-0801842733}}.\n\n* ''The Jews in Poland and Russia: Bibliographical Essays'' (with [[Gershon Bacon]]). Indiana University Press, 1984. {{ISBN|978-0253331588}}.\n\n===Edited Books / Encyclopedia===\n* ''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe'', 2 vols., Editor in Chief. New Haven and London: Yale University Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0300119039}}.\nhttp://www.yivoencyclopedia.org - launched 2010.\n\n* ''Jews in Early Modern Poland''. [Polin, Volume 10] Oxford: The Littman Library of Jewish Civilization in association with Vallentine Mitchell, 1997. {{ISBN|978-1874774310}}.\n\n* ''Jews, Poles, Socialists: The Failure of an Ideal''. [Polin, Volume 9] (edited with [[Antony Polonsky]], [[Israel Bartal]], [[Magdalena Opalski]] and [[Jerzy Tomaszewski (historian)|Jerzy Tomaszewski]]). Oxford: The Littman Library of Jewish Civilization in association with Vallentine Mitchell, 1996. {{ISBN|9781874774211}}.\n\n* ''Essential Papers on Hasidism: Origins to Present''. New York University Press, 1991. {{ISBN|978-0814734704}}.\n\n* ''Community and the Individual Jew: Essays in Honor of Lavy M. Becker''. (edited with Ronald S. Aigen). Montreal, Reconstructionist Rabbinical College Press, 1986. {{ISBN|978-0938945000}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\nTalk: Record of Jewish Merchant from the 18th Century, the Newest Materials.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t36ln-WbOyY\n\nTalk: Jews and Other Poles: Problems of Language.\nhttps://www.