{"title_page": "Gerry Carroll", "text_new": "{{for|the Gaelic footballer|Gerry Carroll (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Gerry Carroll\n| office             = Member of <br />[[Belfast City Council]]\n| order              = \n| honorific-prefix   = \n| honorific-suffix   = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]]\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Gerry Carroll 2016.jpg\n| alt                = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be-->\n| caption            = Carroll in 2016\n| alongside          = six others\n| constituency       = [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]]\n| predecessor        = ''Office created''\n| successor          = Matthew Collins\n| constituency_AM1   = [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]]\n| assembly1          = Northern Ireland\n| term_start1        = 7 May 2016\n| term_end1          = \n| predecessor1       = [[Rosie McCorley]]\n| party              = [[People Before Profit]]\n| prior_term         =\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|27 April 1987}}\n| birth_place        = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Ulster]]\n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| committees         = \n| term_start         = 22 May 2014\n| term_end           = 7 May 2016\n}}\n\n'''Gerry Carroll''' (born 27 April 1987) is a [[People Before Profit]] politician from [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], who has represented the [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]] constituency in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] since May 2016. From 2014 until 2016 he also represented the [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]] district electoral area on [[Belfast City Council]].\n\n==Career==\nWhen aged 16, Carroll fund-raised with fellow activists to travel to [[Edinburgh]] for the [[Make Poverty History]] protest. He contested the [[2011 Belfast West by-election]]\u2014triggered by the resignation of [[Gerry Adams]]\u2014for the [[People Before Profit]], and won 7.6% of the vote. At the [[2014 Belfast City Council election]] he gained one of the seven seats in the [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]] electoral area from [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], coming third. Following his election, he said that he did not describe himself as a [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] or a [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]], instead choosing to identify as a [[Socialism|socialist]]. He said: \"There is a lot of anger in West Belfast at the minute over the situation at [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital]]'s [[Emergency department|A&E]], the privatisation of leisure centres and the Casement Park issues...residents have been trampled on\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Rebecca|last=Black|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/i-am-not-a-nationalist-or-a-unionist-i-am-a-socialist-says-people-before-profits-new-belfast-councillor-gerry-carroll-30300411.html|title=I am not a nationalist or a unionist, I am a socialist, says People Before Profit's new Belfast councillor Gerry Carroll|newspaper=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|date=24 May 2014|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> He contested Belfast West again at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2015 (Northern Ireland)|2015 general election]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Tiarn\u00e1n|last=\u00d3 Muilleoir|url=http://belfastmediagroup.com/carroll-vows-to-take-on-austerity-parties/|title=Carroll vows to take on \u2018austerity parties\u2019|publisher=Belfast Media Group|date=6 March 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> this time coming second, gaining 19.2% of the vote and reducing the Sinn F\u00e9in majority from 57.1% to 35.0%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/N06000004|title=Belfast West parliamentary constituency \u2013 Election 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected a councillor, Carroll criticised the large pay rises that were given to councillors whilst other council staff suffered effective pay cuts, and campaigned against privatisation and cuts.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Stewart|url=http://www.belfastlive.co.uk/incoming/politician-expresses-fears-over-waterfront-9539656|title=Politician expresses fears over Waterfront Hall 'privatisation'|publisher=Belfast Live|date=27 June 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe criticised Sinn F\u00e9in's \"support for capitalism\", and spoke against the \"[[Sectarianism|sectarian]] nature\" of politics in Northern Ireland. In August 2014 he said: \"In Northern Ireland sectarianism is at the heart of the state. I don't accept that, but then again I don't accept the conservative right-wing state in the south\". At the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2016 Assembly election]] he was elected an [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]], topping the poll on the first count and gaining a seat from [[Rosie McCorley]] of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{cite web|last=Little|first=Ivan|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/west-belfast-fairy-tale-win-for-newcomer-carroll-as-he-snatches-seat-from-sinn-fein-34692962.html|title=West Belfast: Fairy tale win for newcomer Carroll as he snatches seat from Sinn F\u00e9in|website=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> He was re-elected at the [[2017 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2017 election]]; however, his vote fell from 22.9% to 12.2% in the face of a 4% overall Sinn F\u00e9in vote increase that cost fellow People Before Profit MLA [[Eamonn McCann]] and the [[SDLP]]'s [[Alex Attwood]] their re-election bids.<ref>{{cite news|author=Allison Morris |url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/assemblyelection/2017/03/03/news/west-belfast-only-the-most-optimistic-would-have-predicted-such-a-massive-swing-back-to-sinn-fe-in-951526/ |title=West Belfast: Only the most optimistic would have predicted such a massive swing back to Sinn F\u00e9in |newspaper=[[The Irish News]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nCarroll's support for [[Brexit]], in an area in which three-quarters of voters voted Remain, has attracted criticism from Sinn F\u00e9in and pro-EU activists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinnfein.ie/contents/42032 |title=Carroll and McCann align themselves to Tory right wingers \u2013 Maskey &#124; Sinn F\u00e9in |website=Sinnfein.ie |date=2016-10-18 |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishnews.com/opinion/letterstotheeditor/2016/07/04/news/brexit-fallout-has-undermined-the-principle-of-consent-586751/ |title=People Before Profit's justification for Brexit is just nonsense |newspaper=[[The Irish News]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ni/ass}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Rosie McCorley]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]]\n | years = 2016\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People Before Profit}}\n{{Northern Ireland party leaders}}\n{{Leaders of political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carroll, Gerry}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Ulster University]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2016\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:People Before Profit Alliance MLAs]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Socialists from Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Gaelic footballer|Gerry Carroll (footballer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name               = Gerry Carroll\n| office             = Member of <br />[[Belfast City Council]]\n| order              = \n| honorific-prefix   = \n| honorific-suffix   = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]]\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Gerry Carroll 2016.jpg\n| alt                = \n| smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be-->\n| caption            = Carroll in 2016\n| alongside          = six others\n| constituency       = [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]]\n| predecessor        = ''Office created''\n| successor          = Matthew Collins\n| constituency_AM1   = [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]]\n| assembly1          = Northern Ireland\n| term_start1        = 7 May 2016\n| term_end1          = \n| predecessor1       = [[Rosie McCorley]]\n| party              = [[People Before Profit]]\n| prior_term         =\n| birth_date         = {{birth-date and age|27 April 1987}}\n| birth_place        = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Ulster]]\n| occupation         = Politician\n| profession         = \n| committees         = \n| term_start         = 22 May 2014\n| term_end           = 7 May 2016\n}}\n\n'''Gerry Carroll''' (born 27 April 1987) is a [[People Before Profit]] politician from [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], who has represented the [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]] constituency in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] since May 2016. From 2014 until 2016 he also represented the [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]] district electoral area on [[Belfast City Council]].\n\n==Career==\nWhen aged 16, Carroll fund-raised with fellow activists to travel to [[Edinburgh]] for the [[Make Poverty History]] protest. He contested the [[2011 Belfast West by-election]]\u2014triggered by the resignation of [[Gerry Adams]]\u2014for the [[People Before Profit]], and won 7.6% of the vote. At the [[2014 Belfast City Council election]] he gained one of the seven seats in the [[Black Mountain (District Electoral Area)|Black Mountain]] electoral area from [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], coming third. Following his election, he said that he did not describe himself as a [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] or a [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]], instead choosing to identify as a [[Socialism|socialist]]. He said: \"There is a lot of anger in West Belfast at the minute over the situation at [[Royal Victoria Hospital, Belfast|Royal Victoria Hospital]]'s [[Emergency department|A&E]], the privatisation of leisure centres and the Casement Park issues...residents have been trampled on\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Rebecca|last=Black|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/i-am-not-a-nationalist-or-a-unionist-i-am-a-socialist-says-people-before-profits-new-belfast-councillor-gerry-carroll-30300411.html|title=I am not a nationalist or a unionist, I am a socialist, says People Before Profit's new Belfast councillor Gerry Carroll|newspaper=[[The Belfast Telegraph]]|date=24 May 2014|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> He contested Belfast West again at the [[United Kingdom general election, 2015 (Northern Ireland)|2015 general election]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Tiarn\u00e1n|last=\u00d3 Muilleoir|url=http://belfastmediagroup.com/carroll-vows-to-take-on-austerity-parties/|title=Carroll vows to take on \u2018austerity parties\u2019|publisher=Belfast Media Group|date=6 March 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref> this time coming second, gaining 19.2% of the vote and reducing the Sinn F\u00e9in majority from 57.1% to 35.0%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/politics/constituencies/N06000004|title=Belfast West parliamentary constituency \u2013 Election 2015|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter being elected a councillor, Carroll criticised the large pay rises that were given to councillors whilst other council staff suffered effective pay cuts, and campaigned against privatisation and cuts.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Stewart|url=http://www.belfastlive.co.uk/incoming/politician-expresses-fears-over-waterfront-9539656|title=Politician expresses fears over Waterfront Hall 'privatisation'|publisher=Belfast Live|date=27 June 2015|accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe criticised Sinn F\u00e9in's \"support for capitalism\", and spoke against the \"[[Sectarianism|sectarian]] nature\" of politics in Northern Ireland. In August 2014 he said: \"In Northern Ireland sectarianism is at the heart of the state. I don't accept that, but then again I don't accept the conservative right-wing state in the south\". At the [[2016 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2016 Assembly election]] he was elected an [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]], topping the poll on the first count and gaining a seat from [[Rosie McCorley]] of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{cite web|last=Little|first=Ivan|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/west-belfast-fairy-tale-win-for-newcomer-carroll-as-he-snatches-seat-from-sinn-fein-34692962.html|title=West Belfast: Fairy tale win for newcomer Carroll as he snatches seat from Sinn F\u00e9in|website=BelfastTelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=20 May 2016}}</ref> He was re-elected at the [[2017 Northern Ireland Assembly election|2017 election]]; however, his vote fell from 22.9% to 12.2% in the face of a 4% overall Sinn F\u00e9in vote increase that cost fellow People Before Profit MLA [[Eamonn McCann]] and the [[SDLP]]'s [[Alex Attwood]] their re-election bids.<ref>{{cite news|author=Allison Morris |url=http://www.irishnews.com/news/assemblyelection/2017/03/03/news/west-belfast-only-the-most-optimistic-would-have-predicted-such-a-massive-swing-back-to-sinn-fe-in-951526/ |title=West Belfast: Only the most optimistic would have predicted such a massive swing back to Sinn F\u00e9in |newspaper=[[The Irish News]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\nCarroll's support for [[Brexit]], in an area in which three-quarters of voters voted Remain, has attracted criticism from Sinn F\u00e9in and pro-EU activists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinnfein.ie/contents/42032 |title=Carroll and McCann align themselves to Tory right wingers \u2013 Maskey &#124; Sinn F\u00e9in |website=Sinnfein.ie |date=2016-10-18 |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishnews.com/opinion/letterstotheeditor/2016/07/04/news/brexit-fallout-has-undermined-the-principle-of-consent-586751/ |title=People Before Profit's justification for Brexit is just nonsense |newspaper=[[The Irish News]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-04}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|ni/ass}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Rosie McCorley]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (Northern Ireland)|MLA]] for [[Belfast West (Assembly constituency)|Belfast West]]\n | years = 2016\u2013present\n}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People Before Profit}}\n{{Northern Ireland party leaders}}\n{{Leaders of political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carroll, Gerry}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Ulster University]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2016\u20132017]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:People Before Profit Alliance MLAs]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Socialists from Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerry_Carroll"}
{"title_page": "Grant Hardy", "text_new": "{{Over-quotation|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Grant R. Hardy\n| image              = Grant Hardy.png\n| birth_name         = Grant Ricardo Hardy<ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes |first=Kevin S |url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3AHardy%2C+Grant+Ricardo.&qt=hot_author |title=Results for 'au:Hardy, Grant Ricardo.' |publisher=Worldcat.org |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|03|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]]\n| home_town          = [[Paradise, California]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Heather Burris Nylander |url=http://www.phsclassreunion.com/class_profile.cfm?member_id=2775274 |title=Grant Hardy, Paradise, CA California currently in Asheville, NC USA |publisher=Phsclassreunion.com |date=2018-03-07 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| nationality        = \n| known_for          = [[Book of Mormon]] studies\n| residence          = [[Asheville, North Carolina]]\n| education          = [[Brigham Young University]] (BA)<br />[[Yale University]] (PhD)\n| spouse             = Heather Nielsen Hardy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fairmormon.org/testimonies/scholars/grant-hardy |title=Grant Hardy |publisher=FairMormon |date=2017-07-21 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://history.unca.edu/faces/faculty/grant-hardy}}\n| awards             = \n| occupation         = Professor\n| employer           = [[University of North Carolina at Asheville]] (1994\u2013present)\n| module             = \n}}\n'''Grant Hardy''' is professor of history and [[religious studies]] and director of the humanities program at the [[University of North Carolina at Asheville]]. He earned his B.A. in [[ancient Greek]] in 1984 from [[Brigham Young University]] and his Ph.D. in [[Chinese language]] [[Chinese literature|and literature]] from [[Yale University]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegreatcourses.com/professors/grant-hardy/ |title=Professor Bio Page |publisher=Thegreatcourses.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref> Having written, cowritten, or edited several books in the fields of [[history]], [[humanities]], and religious texts as literature, Hardy is known for literary studies of the [[Book of Mormon]].\n\n== Mormon studies ==\n=== Book of Mormon study editions and notes ===\nHardy's contributions in [[Mormon studies]] are ''The Book of Mormon: A Reader's Edition'' (2003), ''Understanding the Book of Mormon: A Readers' Guide'' (2010) and ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ: Maxwell Institute Study Edition,'' (2018).<ref name =10q>{{cite web|last=Manwaring |first=Kurt |url=http://www.fromthedesk.org/10-questions-spencer-fluhman/ |title=10 questions with Spencer Fluhman |publisher=From The Desk |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref>[https://deseretbook.com/p/rsc-book-of-mormon-another-testament-of-jesus-christ-maxwell-institute-study-guide?variant_id=169323-paperback Publication information on the Maxwell Institute Book of Mormon edition]</ref>\n\n==== Reception ====\n;Individual works\nAccording to a review by Michael Austin of ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ, Maxwell Institute Study Edition'' (2018; Hardy, ed.), \"By combining with a serious and thoughtful scholar like Grant Hardy, the [LDS] Church has produced and authorized a version of its signature scripture that is orders of magnitude more helpful, and more scholarly, than anything it has produced before.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url = https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/issues/V52N02a.pdf|journal = [[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]|pages = 173&ndash;181|date = Summer 2019|author = Michael Austin|title = 'Reasonably Good Tidings of Greater-than-Average Joy': Grant Hardy, ed. ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ, Maxwell Institute Study Edition.''}}</ref>\n\nHardy's ''Understanding the Book of Mormon'' (2010) has been received favorably for what its publisher, [[Oxford University Press]], describes as \"comprehensive analysis of the work's narrative structure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=related:a0twW6KT0lQJ:scholar.google.com/&hl=en&as_sdt=0,5#d=gs_qabs&p=&u=%23p%3DT7fpI1-W5AwJ |title=Google Scholar |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n;In general\nGrant Shreve says the Book of Mormon's text, \"once derided as 'a fiction of hob-goblins and bugbears,'\" now is being examined by non-Mormon academics and university students, its inclusion on syllabi facilitated by \"attractive reader\u2019s editions of the Book of Mormon armed with immaculate scholarly introductions framing it for non-Mormon audiences\" by Hardy (2005) and also by Laurie Maffly-Kipp (2008, Penguin).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://religionandpolitics.org/2017/05/23/the-book-of-mormon-gets-the-literary-treatment/ |title=The Book of Mormon Gets the Literary Treatment &#124; Religion & Politics |publisher=Religionandpolitics.org |date=2016-01-19 |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref>\n\nNeal Rappleye, in the Mormon apologetics journal ''Interpreter,'' lauds Hardy's demonstrations of the Book of Mormon's \"depth and complexity, multiple voices, and insightful readings,\" that Rappleye believes bolsters its truth claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interpreterfoundation.org/creating-a-list-of-standard-works-on-book-of-mormon-authenticity/ |title=Creating a List of \"Standard Works\" on Book of Mormon Authenticity |publisher=The Interpreter Foundation |date=2014-01-06 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the ''Journal of Book of Mormon Studies'' devoted an issue to Hardy's Book of Mormon studies, its editor saying, \"We see his work as crucially transitional, bringing the scripture increasingly to the attention of the broader academy.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Hauglid |url=https://mi.byu.edu/hauglid-intro-jbms-25/ |title=Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship |publisher=Mi.byu.edu |date=2016-04-22 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Apologetics ===\nHardy, a Latter-day Saint, has joined proponents advocating tolerance within the faith for struggles with doubt. Providing context for his work, in his August 5, 2016 address at the annual [[FairMormon]] conference, he said, \"Academics have little interest in debates about whether Mormonism is true or false, but they are increasingly interested in Mormonism as a religious and social movement.\"<ref name=\"fairmormon1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fairmormon.org/conference/august-2016/more-effective-apologetics |title=More Effective Apologetics |publisher=FairMormon |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> When asked during the   question-and-answer session concerning believers who harbor questions about the [[historicity of the Book of Mormon|Book of Mormon's historicity]], he said, \"Can faith in the Book of Mormon as inspired fiction be a saving faith? And I think the answer is, absolutely.\"<ref name=\"fairmormon1\" />\n\nA two-part 2017 article by Duane Boyce in the [[Mormon apologetics|LDS apologetics]] journal ''[[Interpreter (journal)|Interpreter]]'' questions the didactic effectiveness of Hardy's study's ascriptions of possible psychological motives to individuals categorized as [[list of Book of Mormon prophets|prophets within the Book of Mormon]]. Boyce believes literary analysis of this type retrograde to the book's divine purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mormoninterpreter.com/a-lengthening-shadow-is-quality-of-thought-deteriorating-in-lds-scholarly-discourse-regarding-prophets-and-revelation-part-two/ |title=A Lengthening Shadow: Is Quality of Thought Deteriorating in LDS Scholarly Discourse Regarding Prophets and Revelation? Part Two &#124; Interpreter: A Journal of Mormon Scripture |publisher=Mormoninterpreter.com |date=2017-07-28 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> [[Ralph C. Hancock]] published in ''Interpreter'' his argument that Hardy\u2019s reading of the Book of Mormon is \"in a way more religious than any other because it is more rational\u2014that is, by allowing natural questions to arise and to resonate, he reveals characters to us (especially the three authors\" <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Plates of Nephi|Nephi]], [[Book of Mormon (Mormon's record)|Mormon]], and [[Book of Moroni|Moroni]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> \"that are more miraculous because they are more human.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.mormoninterpreter.com/to-really-read-the-book-of-mormon/ |title = To Really Read the Book of Mormon|journal = Interpreter: A Journal of Latter-Day Saint Faith and Scholarship|volume = 1|year = 2012|last1 = Hancock|first1 = Ralph C.}}</ref>\n\n=== Background: Opening the Book of Mormon studies sub-discipline ===\n{{See also|Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|Textual criticism#Book of Mormon|Mormonism and history#Tension between faith and scholarship}}\n\nStudies of the ''[[Book of Mormon]]''\u2013the foundational scripture of the [[LDS Church|Latter-day Saints]]\u2013usually were  apologetic (devotional) or polemical ([[criticism of Mormon sacred texts#Book of Mormon|critical of its truth claims]]) prior to about 2010. Parallel the burgeoning of [[Mormon studies]] generally as a field of more neutral scholarship in early 21st century, university courses began including [[literary studies]] of this book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://religionandpolitics.org/2017/05/23/the-book-of-mormon-gets-the-literary-treatment/ |title=The Book of Mormon Gets the Literary Treatment &#124; Religion & Politics |publisher=Religionandpolitics.org |date=2016-01-19 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Nicholas J. Frederick said, \"With a few notable exceptions, such as [[Philip Barlow]]\u2019s ''Mormons and the Bible'' and Grant Hardy\u2019s ''Understanding the Book of Mormon,'' full-length monographs devoted to [Book of Mormon studies] have been lacking.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=J. Frederick |url=https://rowman.com/ISBN/9781611479065/The-Bible-Mormon-Scripture-and-the-Rhetoric-of-Allusivity# |title=The Bible, Mormon Scripture, and the Rhetoric of Allusivity \u2013 9781611479065 \u2013 Rowman & Littlefield |publisher=Rowman.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> In 2017, organizers of a Book of Mormon studies symposium classed Hardy's scholarship, that brings \"the content and the depth of the Book of Mormon into the larger academic world\"; some recent scholarship of academics affiliated with the Mormons' principal rival within the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], [[Community of Christ]]; and the papers published in the ''Journal of Book of Mormon Studies,'' as important contributions in its field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/faithpromotingrumor/2017/02/call-papers-book-mormon-studies/ |title=Call for Papers: Book of Mormon Studies |publisher=Patheos.com |date= 2017-02-16|accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n===Books===\nIn addition to chapters and journal articles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.unca.edu/faces/faculty/grant-hardy |title=Grant Hardy, Ph.D. &#124; Department of History |publisher=History.unca.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.mi.byu.edu/people/grant-r-hardy/ |title=Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship |publisher=Publications.mi.byu.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref> Hardy has published the following books:\n*{{cite book|series = Oxford History of Historical Writing|volume = 1|title = Beginnings to AD 600|editors = (Co-editor) Andrew Feldherr|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2015}}\n*{{cite book|title = Understanding the Book of Mormon: A Readers' Guide|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2010|isbn = 978-0-19-974544-9}}\n*{{cite book|title = The Book of Mormon: A Reader's Edition|publisher = [[University of Illinois Press]]|year = 2003|editor = Grant Hardy}}\n*{{cite book|title = The Establishment of the Han Empire and Imperial China|series = Greenwood guides to historic events of the ancient world|author = (Co-author) Anne Behnke Kinney|publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|year = 2005|isbn = 978-0-313-32588-5|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/establishmentofh00gran}}\n*{{cite book|title = Worlds of Bronze and Bamboo: Sima Qian's Conquest of History|publisher = [[Columbia University Press]]|year = 1999|isbn = 978-0-231-50451-5}}\n\n===Chapter===\n*{{cite book|chapter = Textual Criticism and the Book of Mormon|pages = 37&ndash;73|title = Foundational Texts of Mormonism|\neditors = [[Mark Ashurst-McGee]], Robin Scott Jensen & Sharalyn D. Howcroft|publisher\t= [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2018|isbn = 9780190274405}}<ref>http://m.oxfordscholarship.com/mobile/view/10.1093/oso/9780190274375.001.0001/oso-9780190274375-chapter-3</ref>\n\n== Multimedia ==\n*{{cite book|title = Sacred Texts of the World|series = [[The Great Courses]]|publisher = Teaching Company|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1-62997-044-8|type = audio of 36 lectures as narrated by Grant Hardy}}\n*{{cite book|title = Great Minds of the Eastern Intellectual Tradition|series = [[The Great Courses]]|publisher = Teaching Company|year = 2011|isbn = 978-1-59803-742-5}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Origin of the Book of Mormon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2002105051/}}\n*{{cite AV media\n | people = Interview of Grant Hardy & Heather Hardy by [[John Dehlin]]\n | date = April 5, 2011\n | title = Book of Mormon Scholarship\n | url = https://www.mormonstories.org/podcast/250-251-grant-heather-hardy-book-of-mormon-scholarship/\n | publisher = [[Mormon Stories]]\n | medium = audio\n}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardy, Grant}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Asheville faculty]]\n[[Category:Mormon apologists]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from California]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Over-quotation|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Grant R. Hardy\n| image              = Grant Hardy.png\n| birth_name         = Grant Ricardo Hardy<ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes |first=Kevin S |url=http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=au%3AHardy%2C+Grant+Ricardo.&qt=hot_author |title=Results for 'au:Hardy, Grant Ricardo.' |publisher=Worldcat.org |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|03|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Chicago]]\n| home_town          = [[Paradise, California]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Heather Burris Nylander |url=http://www.phsclassreunion.com/class_profile.cfm?member_id=2775274 |title=Grant Hardy, Paradise, CA California currently in Asheville, NC USA |publisher=Phsclassreunion.com |date=2018-03-07 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| nationality        = \n| known_for          = [[Book of Mormon]] studies\n| residence          = [[Asheville, North Carolina]]\n| education          = [[Brigham Young University]] (BA)<br />[[Yale University]] (PhD)\n| spouse             = Heather Nielsen Hardy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fairmormon.org/testimonies/scholars/grant-hardy |title=Grant Hardy |publisher=FairMormon |date=2017-07-21 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n| website            = {{URL|https://history.unca.edu/faces/faculty/grant-hardy}}\n| awards             = \n| occupation         = Professor\n| employer           = [[University of North Carolina at Asheville]] (1994\u2013present)\n| module             = \n}}\n'''Grant Hardy''' is professor of history and [[religious studies]] and director of the humanities program at the [[University of North Carolina at Asheville]]. He earned his B.A. in [[ancient Greek]] in 1984 from [[Brigham Young University]] and his Ph.D. in [[Chinese language]] [[Chinese literature|and literature]] from [[Yale University]] in 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegreatcourses.com/professors/grant-hardy/ |title=Professor Bio Page |publisher=Thegreatcourses.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref> Having written, cowritten, or edited several books in the fields of [[history]], [[humanities]], and religious texts as literature, Hardy is known for literary studies of the [[Book of Mormon]].\n\n== Mormon studies ==\n=== Book of Mormon study editions and notes ===\nHardy's contributions in [[Mormon studies]] are ''The Book of Mormon: A Reader's Edition'' (2003), ''Understanding the Book of Mormon: A Readers' Guide'' (2010) and ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ: Maxwell Institute Study Edition,'' (2018).<ref name =10q>{{cite web|last=Manwaring |first=Kurt |url=http://www.fromthedesk.org/10-questions-spencer-fluhman/ |title=10 questions with Spencer Fluhman |publisher=From The Desk |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref>[https://deseretbook.com/p/rsc-book-of-mormon-another-testament-of-jesus-christ-maxwell-institute-study-guide?variant_id=169323-paperback Publication information on the Maxwell Institute Book of Mormon edition]</ref>\n\n==== Reception ====\n;Individual works\nAccording to a review by Michael Austin of ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ, Maxwell Institute Study Edition'' (2018; Hardy, ed.), \"By combining with a serious and thoughtful scholar like Grant Hardy, the [LDS] Church has produced and authorized a version of its signature scripture that is orders of magnitude more helpful, and more scholarly, than anything it has produced before.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url = https://www.dialoguejournal.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/issues/V52N02a.pdf|journal = [[Dialogue: A Journal of Mormon Thought]]|pages = 173&ndash;181|date = Summer 2019|author = Michael Austin|title = 'Reasonably Good Tidings of Greater-than-Average Joy': Grant Hardy, ed. ''The Book of Mormon: Another Testament of Jesus Christ, Maxwell Institute Study Edition.''}}</ref>\n\nHardy's ''Understanding the Book of Mormon'' (2010) has been received favorably for what its publisher, [[Oxford University Press]], describes as \"comprehensive analysis of the work's narrative structure.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=related:a0twW6KT0lQJ:scholar.google.com/&hl=en&as_sdt=0,5#d=gs_qabs&p=&u=%23p%3DT7fpI1-W5AwJ |title=Google Scholar |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n;In general\nGrant Shreve says the Book of Mormon's text, \"once derided as 'a fiction of hob-goblins and bugbears,'\" now is being examined by non-Mormon academics and university students, its inclusion on syllabi facilitated by \"attractive reader\u2019s editions of the Book of Mormon armed with immaculate scholarly introductions framing it for non-Mormon audiences\" by Hardy (2005) and also by Laurie Maffly-Kipp (2008, Penguin).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://religionandpolitics.org/2017/05/23/the-book-of-mormon-gets-the-literary-treatment/ |title=The Book of Mormon Gets the Literary Treatment &#124; Religion & Politics |publisher=Religionandpolitics.org |date=2016-01-19 |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref>\n\nNeal Rappleye, in the Mormon apologetics journal ''Interpreter,'' lauds Hardy's demonstrations of the Book of Mormon's \"depth and complexity, multiple voices, and insightful readings,\" that Rappleye believes bolsters its truth claims.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interpreterfoundation.org/creating-a-list-of-standard-works-on-book-of-mormon-authenticity/ |title=Creating a List of \"Standard Works\" on Book of Mormon Authenticity |publisher=The Interpreter Foundation |date=2014-01-06 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the ''Journal of Book of Mormon Studies'' devoted an issue to Hardy's Book of Mormon studies, its editor saying, \"We see his work as crucially transitional, bringing the scripture increasingly to the attention of the broader academy.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Brian Hauglid |url=https://mi.byu.edu/hauglid-intro-jbms-25/ |title=Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship |publisher=Mi.byu.edu |date=2016-04-22 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Apologetics ===\nHardy, a Latter-day Saint, has joined proponents advocating tolerance within the faith for struggles with doubt. Providing context for his work, in his August 5, 2016 address at the annual [[FairMormon]] conference, he said, \"Academics have little interest in debates about whether Mormonism is true or false, but they are increasingly interested in Mormonism as a religious and social movement.\"<ref name=\"fairmormon1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fairmormon.org/conference/august-2016/more-effective-apologetics |title=More Effective Apologetics |publisher=FairMormon |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> When asked during the   question-and-answer session concerning believers who harbor questions about the [[historicity of the Book of Mormon|Book of Mormon's historicity]], he said, \"Can faith in the Book of Mormon as inspired fiction be a saving faith? And I think the answer is, absolutely.\"<ref name=\"fairmormon1\" />\n\nA two-part 2017 article by Duane Boyce in the [[Mormon apologetics|LDS apologetics]] journal ''[[Interpreter (journal)|Interpreter]]'' questions the didactic effectiveness of Hardy's study's ascriptions of possible psychological motives to individuals categorized as [[list of Book of Mormon prophets|prophets within the Book of Mormon]]. Boyce believes literary analysis of this type retrograde to the book's divine purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mormoninterpreter.com/a-lengthening-shadow-is-quality-of-thought-deteriorating-in-lds-scholarly-discourse-regarding-prophets-and-revelation-part-two/ |title=A Lengthening Shadow: Is Quality of Thought Deteriorating in LDS Scholarly Discourse Regarding Prophets and Revelation? Part Two &#124; Interpreter: A Journal of Mormon Scripture |publisher=Mormoninterpreter.com |date=2017-07-28 |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> [[Ralph C. Hancock]] published in ''Interpreter'' his argument that Hardy\u2019s reading of the Book of Mormon is \"in a way more religious than any other because it is more rational\u2014that is, by allowing natural questions to arise and to resonate, he reveals characters to us (especially the three authors\" <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Plates of Nephi|Nephi]], [[Book of Mormon (Mormon's record)|Mormon]], and [[Book of Moroni|Moroni]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> \"that are more miraculous because they are more human.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | url=https://www.mormoninterpreter.com/to-really-read-the-book-of-mormon/ |title = To Really Read the Book of Mormon|journal = Interpreter: A Journal of Latter-Day Saint Faith and Scholarship|volume = 1|year = 2012|last1 = Hancock|first1 = Ralph C.}}</ref>\n\n=== Background: Opening the Book of Mormon studies sub-discipline ===\n{{See also|Allegorical interpretation of the Bible|Textual criticism#Book of Mormon|Mormonism and history#Tension between faith and scholarship}}\n\nStudies of the ''[[Book of Mormon]]''\u2013the foundational scripture of the [[LDS Church|Latter-day Saints]]\u2013usually were  apologetic (devotional) or polemical ([[criticism of Mormon sacred texts#Book of Mormon|critical of its truth claims]]) prior to about 2010. Parallel the burgeoning of [[Mormon studies]] generally as a field of more neutral scholarship in early 21st century, university courses began including [[literary studies]] of this book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://religionandpolitics.org/2017/05/23/the-book-of-mormon-gets-the-literary-treatment/ |title=The Book of Mormon Gets the Literary Treatment &#124; Religion & Politics |publisher=Religionandpolitics.org |date=2016-01-19 |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Nicholas J. Frederick said, \"With a few notable exceptions, such as [[Philip Barlow]]\u2019s ''Mormons and the Bible'' and Grant Hardy\u2019s ''Understanding the Book of Mormon,'' full-length monographs devoted to [Book of Mormon studies] have been lacking.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=J. Frederick |url=https://rowman.com/ISBN/9781611479065/The-Bible-Mormon-Scripture-and-the-Rhetoric-of-Allusivity# |title=The Bible, Mormon Scripture, and the Rhetoric of Allusivity \u2013 9781611479065 \u2013 Rowman & Littlefield |publisher=Rowman.com |date= |accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref> In 2017, organizers of a Book of Mormon studies symposium classed Hardy's scholarship, that brings \"the content and the depth of the Book of Mormon into the larger academic world\"; some recent scholarship of academics affiliated with the Mormons' principal rival within the [[Latter Day Saint movement]], [[Community of Christ]]; and the papers published in the ''Journal of Book of Mormon Studies,'' as important contributions in its field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patheos.com/blogs/faithpromotingrumor/2017/02/call-papers-book-mormon-studies/ |title=Call for Papers: Book of Mormon Studies |publisher=Patheos.com |date= 2017-02-16|accessdate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n===Books===\nIn addition to chapters and journal articles,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://history.unca.edu/faces/faculty/grant-hardy |title=Grant Hardy, Ph.D. &#124; Department of History |publisher=History.unca.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.mi.byu.edu/people/grant-r-hardy/ |title=Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship |publisher=Publications.mi.byu.edu |date= |accessdate=2018-04-19}}</ref> Hardy has published the following books:\n*{{cite book|series = Oxford History of Historical Writing|volume = 1|title = Beginnings to AD 600|editors = (Co-editor) Andrew Feldherr|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2015}}\n*{{cite book|title = Understanding the Book of Mormon: A Readers' Guide|publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2010|isbn = 978-0-19-974544-9}}\n*{{cite book|title = The Book of Mormon: A Reader's Edition|publisher = [[University of Illinois Press]]|year = 2003|editor = Grant Hardy}}\n*{{cite book|title = The Establishment of the Han Empire and Imperial China|series = Greenwood guides to historic events of the ancient world|author = (Co-author) Anne Behnke Kinney|publisher = [[Greenwood Publishing Group]]|year = 2005|isbn = 978-0-313-32588-5|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/establishmentofh00gran}}\n*{{cite book|title = Worlds of Bronze and Bamboo: Sima Qian's Conquest of History|publisher = [[Columbia University Press]]|year = 1999|isbn = 978-0-231-50451-5}}\n\n===Chapter===\n*{{cite book|chapter = Textual Criticism and the Book of Mormon|pages = 37&ndash;73|title = Foundational Texts of Mormonism|\neditors = [[Mark Ashurst-McGee]], Robin Scott Jensen & Sharalyn D. Howcroft|publisher\t= [[Oxford University Press]]|year = 2018|isbn = 9780190274405}}<ref>http://m.oxfordscholarship.com/mobile/view/10.1093/oso/9780190274375.001.0001/oso-9780190274375-chapter-3</ref>\n\n== Multimedia ==\n*{{cite book|title = Sacred Texts of the World|series = [[The Great Courses]]|publisher = Teaching Company|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1-62997-044-8|type = audio of 36 lectures as narrated by Grant Hardy}}\n*{{cite book|title = Great Minds of the Eastern Intellectual Tradition|series = [[The Great Courses]]|publisher = Teaching Company|year = 2011|isbn = 978-1-59803-742-5}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Origin of the Book of Mormon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{worldcat id|id=lccn-n2002105051/}}\n*{{cite AV media\n | people = Interview of Grant Hardy & Heather Hardy by [[John Dehlin]]\n | date = April 5, 2011\n | title = Book of Mormon Scholarship\n | url = https://www.mormonstories.org/podcast/250-251-grant-heather-hardy-book-of-mormon-scholarship/\n | publisher = [[Mormon Stories]]\n | medium = audio\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardy, Grant}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Asheville faculty]]\n[[Category:Mormon apologists]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from California]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grant_Hardy"}
{"title_page": "Hima Shankar", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Hima Shankar\n| image        = \n|caption      = \n| birth_name   = Hima Shankar\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1987|06|02|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kodakara]], [[Thrissur district|Thrissur]], [[Kerala]], [[India]]\n| nationality  = {{Ind}}\n| occupation   = [[Actor|Film actress]]<br>[[Theatre|Theatre Artist]]\n| years_active  = 2004\u2013present\n| alma_mater = [[University of Calicut School of Drama and Fine Arts]]\n}}\n\n'''Hima Shankar''' (born 2 June 1987) known as '''Hima Shankar Sheematty''', is an Indian [[film actress|actress]] <ref>{{cite web|author=CRIS|date=12 August 2017|title=Hima Shankar Sheematty: Actor with an opinion|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/mollywood/120817/actor-with-an-opinion-hima-shankar-sheematty.html|publisher=[[Deccan Chronicle]] |accessdate=2017-10-03}}</ref> who appears in [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam films]] and [[short film]]s. She has also directed and performed in many [[Drama|theatrical works]]. She took a part in the reality show [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam TV series)|Bigg Boss Malayalam]].{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Early life==\nHima Shankar was born on 2 June in [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]], India, to N K Shankaran Kutty and E V Kumari. She did her schooling in St. Don Bosco Girls High School, [[Kodakara]] and intermediate in Rajarshi Memorial Higher Secondary School, [[Aloor, Kerala]]. She has completed her graduation in [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[Vedanta|Sanskrit Vedanta]] from [[Sree Sankaracharya University of Sanskrit]], [[Kalady]]. Subsequently she developed interest in [[theatre]] and joined [[University of Calicut School of Drama and Fine Arts]], [[Thrissur]] for taking up post graduate degree in [[theatre|Theatre Arts]].She played a character called Jennifer in TV serial, Ente Manasaputhri on Asianet.She was part of some advertisements and albums also.She runs an institution also.\nShe is an acting trainer too.\n\n==Career==\nHima Shankar has started her career as a theatre artist later on moving to the [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam Film]] industry. She has enacted in the most discussed plays in [[Malayalam]] which were staged in the 2010s. Being an alumna of the most prestigious Drama School of [[Kerala]], she has succeeded in balancing the engagement on the stage and in the screen. She is found to be an actor with opinion on the current social issues and observed to be outspoken always. Hence, she is a frequent panel member in evening newsroom discussions on social issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LhheaHPj5sc |title=MEET THE EDITORS WITH ACTRESS HIMA SHANKAR\u2502Reporter Live - YouTube |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of the contestant of [[Bigg Boss (Malayalam season 1)]] and got evicted on day 21. Later, she entered the house as a wildcard contestant on day 49.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hima Shankar to take a break after her eviction from the Big .. |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/hima-shankar-to-take-a-break-after-her-eviction-from-the-bigg-boss-malayalam-house/articleshow/65009312.cms |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref> and got eliminated on day 77.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=4 |2010\n|[[Sufi Paranja Katha (film)|Sufi Paranja Katha]]||Parukkutty ||\n|-\n|[[Yugapurushan]]|| Ponni || \n|-\n|[[Apoorvaragam]]|| Agi ||\n|-\n||[[Nalla Pattukare]] ||Reshma||\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Seniors (film)|Seniors]]|| Friend of Jeni ||\n|-\n|2012\n|[[Thalsamayam Oru Penkutty]]|| Neethu||\n|-\n|2013\n|Pothumappu||Susie ||\n|-\n|2014\n|[[Iyobinte Pusthakam]]||Migrant ||\n|-\n|2014\n|Niharika||Special appearance ||\n|-\n|2016\n|Ottakolam|| Aashatty (Lead Role)|| Special Jury Mention in Vayalar Ramavarma Film and Television Awards<ref>{{cite web|author=TNN|title=Vayalar Ramavarma cultural fest from Saturday|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiru